# {{PROJECT_NAME}} Constitution

## Core Principles

### I. Specify-Orchestrated Spec-Driven Delivery (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

Every non-trivial change MUST start from the Specify workflow. The canonical entrypoint is `{{WORKFLOW_ENTRYPOINT}}`, which relies on `/speckit.specify`, `/speckit.plan`, `/speckit.tasks`, `/speckit.analyze`, and `/speckit.implement`. Canonical artifacts MUST live in `{{ARTIFACT_DIR}}/<feature-branch>/`.

### II. Autonomous Workflow with Human Stop Conditions (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

The default process is autonomous end-to-end. Once started, the workflow MUST continue through specification, planning, task generation, implementation, validation, fix round, report updates, and final snapshot without pausing for routine approvals. The workflow MUST stop only for unresolved critical ambiguity, explicit approval of a new technology not already in the approved stack, or an objective gate failure that cannot be resolved automatically.

### III. Quality Gates and {{COVERAGE_THRESHOLD}}% Coverage (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

Repository quality gates are hard delivery gates. Blocking validation MUST pass before a workflow can conclude successfully. Repository coverage MUST remain at `{{COVERAGE_THRESHOLD}}%`, matching the configured threshold in the repo.

### IV. CI Parity Before Completion

"CI green" means parity with the repo's active CI. Blocking gates MUST pass. Observational gates MUST still be executed and recorded in the reports.

### V. Product Direction

The official product direction is `{{PRIMARY_PRODUCT}}`. Legacy surfaces are limited to `{{LEGACY_SURFACE}}` and MUST not become the default target for new delivery.

### VI. Technology Adoption Control

The workflow MUST not silently introduce technology that is not already part of the approved stack. New technology decisions MUST be documented in `research.md`, compare viable alternatives, and emphasize maturity, adoption, documentation quality, lock-in, and cost. The workflow MUST stop for explicit human approval before a new technology is added to the plan or implementation.

### VII. Multi-Workspace Compatibility

The process is agent-agnostic and MUST remain usable across these supported workspaces:

{{SUPPORTED_WORKSPACES}}

